Objects bounce back unnaturally upon contact. Physics calculations are not used. The direction and speed of the bounce are determined randomly, but they are consistent within each piece. 

This piece is a 3D work created using Three.js. You can control the camera by clicking the mouse or tapping the screen. The five colors that can be set with Params are applied randomly to the objects, but each color is used at least once.

The ‰∫∫‰∫∫ collection aims to achieve the simplest possible expression using 3D objects, and this piece is the first in the collection. ‰∫∫‰∫∫ is a Japanese word. The pronunciation is "hitobito," and it means "people."

metadata.name: Miniscapes #264
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: Growth v02 #19
metadata.description:
Growth patterns, version 2. January 2022
Edition of 512

Growth v02 is an generative exploration of patterns in the style of William Morris' iconic wallpaper designs from the 1800s. The code for the Growth series was originally designed to create plausible road networks but has been rewritten to create more organic curved forms. Created with p5js.

'space' to pause the simulation
'h' to toggle to higher res (increases canvas size but runs slower: great for screengrabs)
'r' to reset the seed (some features are locked to the original hash)
's' to save an image to disk
All generated patterns are tile-able horizontally and vertically.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

This project relies heavily on randomly generated values. It has been thoroughly tested. However, there is always the chance that the wrong combination of randomness can create less-compelling growth. If you feel you version is not living up to the potential promised with this piece, please email me.

metadata.name: INTERFERENCES #206
metadata.description:
INTERFERENCES is an abstract representation of the incredible collaboration between artists, collectors and developers on fxhash.

Each edition is composed of a multitude of lines representing each individual on the platform. The color of each line defines the role of each individual in this universe. Through their interactions, and the interferences they produce, each line participates in the creation of a common work.

Happy birthday fxhash! And congratulations to all those who work for its success.

Primary sales are donated to the Processing Foundation

metadata.description:
Dear collectors,
Crayons was originally published as Project #5746 on January 5, 2022.
(https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/5746)
Due to a technical issue, Project #5746 has been hidden from the site and is being replaced by this reissued version.

_______________________________

This art aims to remember the traces of crayons scratching blackboards and even walls, if you prefer. In a child's hands, a crayon represents freedom to draw whatever he wants, even if it's an indefinite scribble. And with these scribbles, I bring to this code the straight, horizontal and vertical lines, which intersect, always mixing two palettes, thus obtaining a perception of incredible depth and texture.

metadata.name: Keep On #46
metadata.description:
One year ago, I published my first Fx(hash) work, "Finding my way". This piece marks its anniversary, and is intended as a THANK YOU to all the people that collected my works. 

It is based on the same algorithm as "Finding my way", i.e. a line growth animated process based on Substrate (Jared Tarbell, 2003) guided by dynamically changing vector fields made with trigonometric functions, but it uses different palettes, more vector fields, and a few more tweakings of the algorithm parameters.

The original piece was intended to symbolise a person's process of finding her/his way. Upon further reflections on the result, I think it more as representing a community process. So here is my wish for the Fx(hash) community, let's keep on finding our way.   

In what now could become a tradition, I've stolen again a palette from the beautiful work of Iskra Velitchkova.

Implemented using various packages from thi.ng/umbrella by Karsten Schmidt, AKA Toxi

metadata.name: Thoughtscapes #98
metadata.description:
Thoughtscapes: A Kaleidoscope of Emotions" is an abstract painting that artfully conveys the intricate relationship between thoughts and feelings. The canvas becomes a canvas of the mind, where emotions and thoughts blend and clash in a symphony of color and form. The bold strokes and rich palette evoke a wide range of feelings. It's an invitation to delve into the kaleidoscope of emotions that shape our lives and reflect upon the beauty that emerges when thoughts and feelings merge on the canvas of our existence.

____________________________________________

The collection is made in pure code with p5.js.

The piece is my first work being published. Hope that you enjoy it!

10% of primary sales are donated to institutions working towards improving biodiversity and environmental efforts.

Key commands:
1 = 1000 px x 1250 px
2 = 2000 px x 2500 px

....
9 = 9000 px x 11250 px

s = export to png using current resolution

I got the idea for this work from playing Prince of Persia 1989 on the SEGA Genesis console. I was playing when the two-dimensional design and angles caught my attention. The main character moves up and down on walls, platforms, and black holes that are designed with 90-degree angles. The environment was very mysterious and mysterious. There were different paths to take. You have to choose the right path, or you may end up on the wrong path and have to turn back the same way.
So I took paper and a pen and, with my imagination, I designed paths with 90-degree angles. Walls that connect and form different paths. I removed the details to show the depth of the paths, but instead, I tried to add different random modes to them. Using various lines and colors and multicolor, two-color, and monochromatic palettes.

Made by p5.js
